Who, what and when:

1936 Peter Gorer

Injects mice with cancer. Mice with different genes from the donor could clear the cancer. He found this was generally true between cells from donor and recepient.

1940s and WWII

Peter Medawar developed these ideas, burns victims focused the mind

1958 HLA gene identified

Thousands have been idenitified to date

DNA, RNA and protein

Possibility, potential and actual | Alleles and allotypes

1986 Alain Townsend

What HLA proteins are showing the immune system

1986 Tim Elliott

1987 Pamela Bjorkman

The structure of the HLA protein

1990 to the present

The peptide loading complex, peptide trimmers etc. etc.

Let's recap

The known knowns

  • There are thousands of these HLA genes
  • We each have up to six
  • HLA proteins present peptides
  • And that's how T-cells know what is going inside cells

The rumsfeldian triplet known knowns: - There are thousands of these HLA genes - We each express up to six HLA allotypes - HLA proteins present peptides - And that's how T-cells know what is going inside cells

Completing the Rumsfeld triplet

  • We don't know the mechanism of peptide generation
  • We don't know the mechanism of peptide selection by HLA
  • We don't know what T-cells are seeing at any given time
  • We don't know what we don't know

The known knowns: The known unknowns The unknown unknowns

Textbook vs. Real life

Interdisciplinary science

What is a contribution?

Some lessons learnt

  • Communication is fundamental.
  • Ensure the question is clear. Invest in problem definition.
  • Design and iterate the set of experiments and models as early as possible.
  • Ideally, do the experiments as well as the analysis.

Predicting HLA peptide selection

Harnessing the power of the immune system

Motivating observations

  • HLA molecules select peptides faster than equilibrium kinetics predict.
  • The higher stability the HLA complex, the more immunogenic it is.
  • Removal of tapasin alters peptide selection in an allotype specific manner.

HLA-B*44:02 and HLA-B*44:05

one amino acid different

A model of peptide selection

Defining the system

  • A general computational systems model of the mechanisms of peptide selection in the absence of tapasin. Shapes represent molecular species and labelled boxes represent reactions and their rate parameters.
  • Different binding mechanisms are illustrated for one-conformation and two-conformation models, where peptide-dependent reactions are indicated by thick red symbols.

  • Comparison of the most likely model (solid lines) against experimental measurements (circles), with 95% confidence intervals (shaded regions).
  • Quantification of pulse chase experiments shown in panel A (circles), together with model simulations (lines). Red indicates the proportion of MHC I molecules that remained after heating to 50C (high affinity peptide-MHC complexes), green indicates heating to 37C (medium and high affinity complexes) and blue indicates heating to 4C (all complexes).
  • Quantification of cell surface transit experiments shown in panel B (circles), together with model simulations (lines).
  • Marginal posterior density of the allele-specific closing rate c, reflecting the probability of the parameter values, conditional on the measured data and underlying model.

Flux analysis of the two-conformation model with peptide-dependent opening (including tapasin) reveals an anti-clockwise cycle of tapasin mediated peptide editing (the peptide-specific reactions are shown as thick red symbols, and grey lines indicate unfavorable reactions).

Three predictions

  • HLA allotype polymorphsims alter protein dynamics
  • Tapasin modulates HLA dynamics to catalyse selection
  • Peptide abundance can overide tapasin or allotype effect

Let's recap again

  • There are thousands of these HLA genes
  • We each have up to six
  • HLA proteins present peptides
  • And that's how T-cells know what is going inside cells
  • HLA molecules can change shape, they are plastic
  • Protein plasticity is part of HLA function

Predicting HLA peptide selection

Harnessing the power of the immune system

  • We need to know what the peptides are and how the population changes
  • We need structural information on these intermediate states
  • Therapies are likely to be stratified
